%md
# Load GS Data to HDFS
Makes queries more efficient by copying the data directly into the HDFS
By moving data into the HDFS, the worker nodes are able to cache some of the data, allowing for subsequent queries to run faster

This can be seen by comparing how long the `SELECT count(countryName) FROM` queries take to run between the `wdi_gs` and `wdi_csv_text` tables
The `wdi_gs` table takes around ~40 seconds every time you run it, as it cannot perform caching due to the data being stored externally
The `wdi_csv_text` table on the other hand, takes aroun ~40 seconds for the first run, and around ~20 seconds for ones afterwards, as the nodes have cached some data

%md
# Hive vs. Bash
Peform the same command using Bash and Hive to compare the two.

Comparing the time it takes to run the `SELECT count(countryName) FROM wdi_csv_text` query above and the Bash script below, you can see that they have a similar running time. This is most likely due to the relatively small size of the data set. The Hive query has a lot of overhead (submitting the job to YARN, distributing the job between the workers, etc.), so the benefit of diving the work between the nodes isn't enough for a data set of this size to make much of a difference.

paragraphs.text:
%md
# Parsing Issue
Determine why a parsing issue occurs

A simple query for distinct indicator codes reveals a strange parsing issue, where values that are clearly not actual indicator codes are being parsed as if they were.
Creating a debug table containing only a single column and querying it for one of the faulty indicator codes reveals the problem: the column before indicator code contains strings, some of which contain the delimiter character `,` as part of their contents. This is causing the default SerDe to split the rows up improperly, causing the incorrect indicator codes.
The issue was resolved by creating a new gs table, using the OpenCSVSerd, and then copying that into a new HDFS text table. As seen below, this fixed the issue, although not without some trade offs. Comparing the `count(countryName)` query's running time between `wdi_csv_text` and the new `wdi_opencsv_text` tables, and you see that the latter takes almost 4 times longer than the original. This is due to the SerDe requiring more time to parse, as it does things like group together strings between quotation marks, essentially trading some speed for more accuracy.

# Hive Partitions
Use Hive partitions to speed up the Canada GDP growth query

To speed up the Canada GDP growth query, we can create a new table with a dynamic partition on the year column. This will change how the table is stored in the HDFS, creating a directory for each value of year found in the column, and storing all rows with that year value in that directory. When running the query on this new, partitioned table, the time it took was greatly reduced, from around 80 seconds to about 4. This is due to the query only having to look in the `year=2015` directory, which is much smaller than the entire dataset.

# Columnar File Optimization
Compare tables stored in columnar formats to those stored in regular row formats.

If we take the table data and store it as a columnar format, such as a parquet, it would reduce the amount of space the table takes up, as the more homogenous data found in columns can be compressed much easier. The difference can be seen in the comparison below, where the parquet table takes up a fraction of the space the original one does.
Additionally, the parquet table is also faster at performing some queries. Compare the Canada 2015 GDP query below to the one on the `wdi_opencsv_text` table above. The parquet one is much faster, as a columnar format allows the query to simply ignore any columns which are not needed.
